  "prompt": "After demonetization of Rs.500 and Rs.1000 notes, what will happen to old notes?",
  "response": "Demonetization refers to the process by which a government declares a particular denomination of its currency as no longer legal tender. In the context of India, demonetization notably occurred on **November 8, 2016**, when the Government of India, led by Prime Minister Narendra Modi, announced the demonetization of all \u20b9500 and \u20b91,000 banknotes. The primary objectives were to curb black money, eliminate counterfeit currency, and promote a digital payment ecosystem.\n\n### **What Happened to the Old \u20b9500 and \u20b91,000 Notes?**\n\n1. **Immediate Invalidity:**\n   - **Cessation as Legal Tender:** From the moment of the announcement, the \u20b9500 and \u20b91,000 notes ceased to be recognized as legal tender. This meant that they could no longer be used for purchasing goods and services or for settling debts.\n   \n2. **Exchange and Deposit Windows:**\n   - **Banks and RBI Offices:** Individuals were given a window, initially up to **two weeks**, during which they could deposit the old notes into their bank accounts or exchange them for new currency. This period was later extended to accommodate the massive influx and address logistical challenges.\n   - **Limits on Deposits and Depository Charges:** To prevent hoarding and limit the misuse of black money, there were restrictions on the amount one could deposit:\n     - **\u20b9500 and \u20b91,000 Notes:** Deposits of a limited number of old \u20b9500 and \u20b91,000 notes were allowed.\n     - **Depository Charges:** For deposits exceeding certain thresholds, charges were levied. For instance, depositing more than \u20b925,000 in a month could attract fees.\n   \n3. **Introduction of New Currency:**\n   - **\u20b92,000 Notes:** To compensate for the demonetization, the government introduced the \u20b92,000 denomination as the new high-value currency note.\n   - **Reintroduction and Adjustments:** Over time, circumstances led to the reintroduction of \u20b9500 notes in November 2016 itself, albeit with enhanced security features to prevent counterfeiting.\n\n4. **Digital Transactions:**\n   - **Encouragement of Digital Payments:** Demonetization acted as a catalyst for the adoption of digital payment methods. With cash being scarce, many turned to online banking, mobile wallets, and other electronic payment systems.\n\n5. **Handling of Excess Notes:**\n   - **Bank Laptops and ATMs:** The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) set up additional facilities, including mobile ATMs and processing centers, to facilitate the deposit and exchange of old notes.\n   - **Unclaimed Currency:** After the stipulated period, unclaimed old notes that were not deposited or exchanged became essentially worthless for transactional purposes.\n\n### **Consequences and Impact**\n\n- **Short-Term Economic Disruption:** The sudden withdrawal of a significant portion of cash led to liquidity shortages, affecting daily wage earners, small businesses, and sectors reliant on cash transactions.\n  \n- **Reduction in Black Money:** While the government aimed to reduce the shadow economy, the effectiveness remains a subject of debate among economists and policymakers.\n\n- **Boost to Digital Economy:** There's been a notable surge in digital transactions post-demonetization, accelerating India's move towards a less-cash economy.\n\n- **Counterfeit Currency:** Initial reports suggested a decline in counterfeit note circulation, although challenges persisted post-demonetization.\n\n### **Long-Term Effects on Old Notes**\n\n- **Non-recirculation:** Post-demonetization, the old \u20b9500 and \u20b91,000 notes do not re-enter the economy. They hold no monetary value for transactions and are not acceptable in financial dealings.\n\n- **Final Closure:** Banks and RBI offices eventually stopped accepting these old notes after the extended exchange windows closed, rendering any remaining old notes obsolete.\n\n### **Summary**\n\nAfter the demonetization of \u20b9500 and \u20b91,000 notes in India:\n\n- **Old Notes Became Invalid:** They were no longer accepted for any financial transactions.\n  \n- **Exchange Periods:** Citizens had specific time frames to deposit or exchange the old notes through banks and RBI channels, subject to certain limits and conditions.\n  \n- **Post-Deadline:** Any old notes not deposited or exchanged within the stipulated periods became worthless for transactional purposes.\n\nDemonetization was a significant economic event with multifaceted impacts, shaping India's financial landscape in the years that followed.",
